review_blob: pours a beautiful oily black with no head and mild lacing. nose of chocolate, coffee, vanilla, and malt. flavor is sweet and creamy, with coffee, anise, and dark fruit notes. oily mouthfeel...nice and thick. finish is long and malty.
beer_name: Brau Brothers Moo Joos Oatmeal Milk Stout

review_blob: pours chestunt-black with a thin tan head. nose of chocolate, roasted malts, vanilla beans. flavor is mostly roasted malt, with some bakers chocolate and coffee. finish is malty and sweet. nice, but a little thin.

pours a beautiful deep chestnut color with a thin, off-white head. nose is heavy with brown sugar, toffee, nuttiness, and a light butterscotch. flavor is similar to aroma, with a bit of breadiness and dark fruit. nice and light, oily with a light bubbliness in the finish. finish is long, with a sweet maple syrup-like flavor balanced by walnut and toffee.
beer_name: Brau Brothers Ring Neck Braun Ale

review_blob: pours deep chestnut brown with a thin tan head. nose of molasses, chocolate, port, and dark fruit. Loads of roasted malt, bakers chocolate, nuttiness, and molasses. long, roasted-malty finish. very enjoyable.

pretty glorious ESB. Pours golden amber with a nice, thick off-white head. nose is heavy with lemon, lemongrass, orange, and spice. flavor is predominantly lemon and spice. nice, well-rounded with the maltiness of the barley. dry and spicy in the finish.

Glorious IPA. Pours a hazy deep orange-gold with a thin white head. nose heavy with caramel, orange, and pine. Flavor is spicy with loads of hops, citrus, and caramel. light brown sugar and doughiness give it a nice chewy mouthfeel. long, bitter aftertaste that gets drier as it sits. Let it warm up a little before drinking it if its in your fridge.
beer_name: Lagunitas A Little Sumpin Sumpin Ale

review_blob: I like the ideology of this beer, being that I live right by the Brandywine. Theres a local pride knowing that the water in this beer is the same stuff running through my faucet. Pours a dark golden-brown with a light haze and an off-white head. nose is piney, with lots of caramel, citrus, and toast. Flavor is nice and bitter in the front, with loads of pine and citrusy hops. On the back end, it changes to a flush of caramel, and a finish of cereal malts and chex. Well-balanced.

decent, easy drinking stout. pours dark brown with a lighter head than Id expect. Nose of chocolate, coffee, roasted malt, and bread dough. medium carbonation, flavors are lighter than Id expect, mainly chocolate, coffee, and roasted malt. on the thinner side. long, roasted malty finish.
Pours a cloudy dark gold/amber with a teafroth off-white head. Nose of light fruit, caramel, honey, toast, and bread dough. Flavor is nice and bitter, with caramel, dough, and lemon. Very dry finish.
Pours light gold with a thin, off-white head. Nice, light summer beer. Light honey, caramel and wheat notes. Medium-dry finish.

Nice, enjoyable pilsener. Pours pale, cloudy straw yellow with a nice, thick white head. Nose of honey, hallertau hops, and biscuit. Flavor is light, floral hops, honey, and biscuit. Nice, dry finish.

pours ruby-amber with a thin off-white head. nose is fruity with caramel, brown sugar, plum, toast, and spice. flavor is roasted malts, brown sugar, light bitter hops, and toast. finish is long, with a dry bitterness develops as it sits on the tongue. Initial mouthfeel is a little too bubbly for my taste, though.

beer_brewer_name: Pretty Things Beer and Ale Project
review_blob: Pretty interesting. Looks like a tripel, with a cloudy amber-orange glow and a decent off-white head. Nose is spicy and citrusy....the standard tripel aromas of banana and clove, along with a more herbal note. Not as fruity as some Ive had. Flavor is nice and herbal, dry, with an alcoholic warmth to it.
beer_name: Pretty Things Fluffy White Rabbits Hoppy Triple

review_blob: pretty solid beer. pours a beautiful chestnut amber-gold with a thin off-white head and minimal lacing. Nose has loads of caramel, sweet bread, toast, a little wood, nuttiness, and spicy, resin-y hops. Flavor is bursting with hops, but it is well-balanced with the maltiness, which contributes a nutty, toasty, roasted hops flavor. Finish is long, bitter, and floral. Nice and dry.
beer_name: Sierra Nevada Harvest Wet Hop IPA - Northern Hemisphere

review_blob: It is what it is. Im a big Star Trek fan, and this beer had huge potential to be awesome due to the quality artwork and packaging, but the beer was absolutely atrocious. I might venture to say it was one of the worst beers Ive ever tasted. Thin, corny, skunky, watered-down. Looked cool, though.

probably the most chocolaty beer Ive ever had. pours a deep brown-black with a teafroth tan head. nose is big with loads of chocolate, cookie dough, and sweet coffee. flavor is milk chocolate, sweet coffee, root beer, and semi-sweet cocoa. aftertaste is long, malty, and chocolaty. mouthfeel is velvety and thick. pretty solid holiday beer.

pours deep amber-chestnut with a thin off-white head. nose of caramel, light fruit, toast, and spices. flavor is toasty, slightly bitter, and citrus. Aftertaste is rather short and bland, with spice and vegetal notes.

pours a cloudy golden orange with a thin off-white head. nose of pine and butterscotch. flavor is heavy butterscotch, pineapple, and caramel. lots of piney hoppiness. resiny aftertaste. nice and dry. very drinkable.

pours a deep chestnut brown/black with very little head. nose is deep and malty, very reminiscent of a scotch ale in my opinion. sweet, roasted malts, coffee, chocolate, and port. flavor is vanilla, a little oakiness, black coffee, chocolate, and a little leather. aftertaste is long, with roasted malts and bitter coffee predominant. a little watery in the mouthfeel, but otherwise pretty good. i used a few cans in my corned beef and cabbage, and it worked out really well.

i think the best thing about this beer is the commercials from a couple years ago. when i first turned 21, i liked this better than the big three beers (i.e., bud, coors, miller) because it was sweeter. when my wife picked up a case the other day, i realized i hadnt ever rated it. that being said, i remember it tasting much better. it pours a nice golden straw color with a decent white head that settles down to a nice thin coating on the beer; light lacing. lots of bubbles. nose is fruity and sweet with honey and light floral hop fragrance prominent. flavor is a little bit more like malt liquor than i remember it being. its sweet, malty, soapy, and watery, and the finish is corny and bland. im sure it would go great with some authentic jerk chicken or another jamaican dish, but as it stands, i dont think im that impressed.

pours a hazy amber, nice smooth body. nose of butterscotch and citrus. flavor is decidedly butterscotch, a little funkiness, a little citrus. finish is long, creamy, and slightly bitter, largely malty.
pours an awesome opaque brown-black with a fluffy tan head. nose of caramel, molasses, dk. fruit. flavor is dark fruit, fig, molasses. Nice malty finish. Smooth mouthfeel.

pours deep brown/black with a thick burnt sienna head. nose has spicy notes, some citrus, chocolate, and dough/yeast. a little licorice and wood in there as well. flavor is huge- lots of roasted malt, espresso with lemon, chocolate, licorice, and bread. finish is long, with notes of bitter coffee, roasted malts, and dough. glorious.
pours deep brown/black with a thin tan head. nose of molasses, coffee, chocolate, smoke, wood, and leather. flavor is malty, with coffee, chocolate, leather, and wood. long, bitter finish.

pours lightly hazy amber orange with a persistent white head. nose of honey, light fruits (nectarine, peach, white grape), and caramel. Flavor is sweet and malty, with honey and grain notes. malty finish. pretty straightforward.

pours a pretty dark burnt sienna with a thick tan head. Hazy. nose of threacle, brown sugar, citrus. flavor is roasted malt, brown sugar, and a light bitter fruitiness. finish is heavy with roasted malt flavors dominating. a little bubbly, slightly creamy.

pours a nice clear amber with a white head and medium lacing. nose of caramel, metallic hops, light and dark fruit. maybe a little woodiness as well. flavor is woody, dry, metallic, caramel, and vanilla. aftertaste is a little bitter, with caramel malts in the background. rounded out by just a touch of diacetyl. more of a banana flavor as it sits. nice, smooth mouthfeel. very enjoyable.

pours a hazy amber orange-yellow with a thin off-white head. nose of peach, citrus, nectarine, pine, and (obviously) spruce. flavor is heavy pine/juniper, caramel, lemon, nectarine. finish is long and dry. soft mouthfeel, lots of lacing.

pours hazy straw gold with a nice off-white head. nose of honey, malt, toast, spice, and oak. flavor is malty- no real hoppiness to it in the onset, just lots of honey, malt, and spice. Then, as it sits, it becomes drier and a little bitter. not bad, but not very much like a true koelsch.

pours a dark orange-amber color with a thin white head. nose of cardamom, orange peel, banana, and clove. flavor is a little toasty, but still mainly a creamy banana citrus flavor. mouthfeel is a little bubbly for me, and not quite thick enough. not bad though.

ok, first off...I dont get the name change. Sun Dog fits much better. Hop HOund makes it sound like theres at least a little hoppiness to it. That being said, it was $10 for a case, so I didnt give it much thought. Its a good lawnmower beer. Pours hazy orange amber with a yellow marble effect from the yeast not evenly dispersing. Big, fluffy off-white head. nose of citrus, papaya, a little soap, and malt. flavor tastes a little like unripe watermelon, with some wheat, malt, and caramel. aftertaste is watermelon-y again, turning a bit odd as it sits. It is what it is.

pours cloudy amber-orange with a fluffy tan head. dark and cloudy with hop sediment. nose of peach, apricot, nectarine, pine, and butterscotch. flavor is hard to place...heavy butterscotch and creme brulee, heavy dried apricot, pine and citrus. slight oakiness too, i think... finish is long and malty...a little bitterness that mellows out as it dries out. not bad, just not what i was expecting.

pours a beautiful clear amber-orange with a thin white head. nose of citrus, pine, floral hops, banana, pineapple, bubblegum, and dough. flavor is pretty close to the smell, but with more prominent hoppiness. solid beer, and a fun break from the stereotypical IPA. bubbly and visocous, but dry on the finish.

2010 bottle @ the whip. pours hazy brown-red with a thin tan head and heavy lacing. nose of dark fruit, esters, caramel, sticky resiny hops, and a little funk. flavor is heavy bitterness, dark and light fruits, caramel, and alcohol. a little bubbly, a little viscous. awesome beer with an awesome dinner.

pretty fun stuff, but not for everybody...I live in Chester County Mushroom Country, Pennsylvania, and my wife and I agreed that this tastes and smells like the local mushroom farms. Kinda an earthy, funky, barnyard umami quality with a definitely fungal characteristic. predominant alcohol flavor as well. yellower than most sakes ive had. i like it, but im probably gonna be the odd one out. If you like exotic mushrooms, youll probably like this.
half as cheap as some of the other comparable lagers. my lawnmower-bbq-garage lager of choice. besides, the baltimore skyline wouldnt be the same without it.

pours deep dark chestnut brown with a thin tan head. nose of caramel, chocolate, and molasses. flavor is heavy molasses and chocolate, with a nice smokiness in the finish, almost like beef jerky. a little bubbly, but thick and chewy.

pours a lovely almost-black brown with a thin beige head. nose is big with caramel, leather, cigar, chocolate, coffee, and roasted malts. a little nutty as well. flavor is big and chocolatey, with a nicely balanced roasted malt flavor and some slight bitter notes as well. finish is long, a little bitterness developing. thick and creamy, almost the consistency of a root beer float. pretty awesome.
had this out of a can at a party last night....my only alternative would have been nati ice. pretty much corn water. blah aftertaste.
pours brown with a thin off-white head. faint nose of malt, dark fruit. flavor is more maltiness, a little brown sugar. dry-ish finish, but a little too watery.

pours hazy yellow with a thin white head. nose of spicy hops, lemongrass, dough. flavor is floral and spicy hops, bread, earth. after is a little off, i think...light sour apple and hops, a little watery.

one of the most stunningly beautiful beers ive ever seen. pours a clear ruby poegranate color with a teafroth white head. incredible lacing. nose heavy with light fruit, fresh strawberry, breadiness, plum, caramel. flavor is dark fruit, caramel, plum, toast, and floral hops. finish is long and bitter turning to maltiness as it lingers.

pours clear amber-orange with a bubbly off-white head. nose of caramel, floral, resin, and spicy hops, light fruit. flavor is full of cascade-y hops goodness. light, but not too light, with a well-balanced malt backbone. palate is slightly bubbly, with a dryness that grows as it sits in your mouth. bitterness grows in the aftertaste. very enjoyable.
beer_name: Great Lakes Burning River Pale Ale

review_blob: pours a deep golden orange-bronze with a light rose tint to it. head is thick and fluffy and off-white with tons of lacing. nose of citrus, bread dough, and a light funkiness. flavor is spicy, lots of citrus, nice bitter floral hop element, toast. slightly bubbly, but with a nice bite. dry, and even drier in the finish. pretty much the best helles Ive ever had. definitely in my top 10 session beer picks.

pours cloudy yellow orange with a thin white head. nose of light fruit, citrus, a little spice. id have thought it was a hefe based on the nose. the taste, though, adds a little bit of citrus with a wallop of cereal malt. theres also a little bit of barnyard funk in there, but its not bad. finish is medium with wheaty notes, then turns a little soapy. i liked the smoothness and the lack of carbonation. drinks easy, decent session beer.

bought a case for a whopping $13 bux. Not bad when you figure out how much that is per bottle. pours a brown/red mahogany. clear with a thin tan teafroth head,. nose of prune, plum, vanilla, malt. flavor is primarily prune and vanilla. I can see where theres a woody element to it, but the flavors not nearly as enticing as the aroma. mouthfeel is a little bubbly, kinda makes my teeth hurt. finish is thin, and leave a malt-extract kinda taste in your mouth.

pours unfiltered straw-orange with a thin, yeasty white head. nose of cardamom, clove, bubblegum, orange, and banana. flavor is light fruit, bubblegum, citrus, yeast. finish is long and estery. nice and dry, not too bubbly.

pours opaque black with a thin brown head. nose of dark fruit, chocolate, coffee, toffee, and smoke. flavor is deep...dark chocolate, mocha, espresso, dark fruit, anise, smoke, and maybe a little bit of leather. finish is dry, intense, and warm. dries out as it lingers. flavors become more pronounced as it sits. a little too bubbly at the start.

pours amber orange with a thin white head, lots of bubbles. nose heavy with brown sugar, pine, resin, pineapple. flavor is grapefruit, pineapple, pine, tropical fruit. slight bubblegummy sweetness in the back, some toastiness as well.  chewy and smooth. finish is long and piney.

Seemed fitting to rate this one on St. Patricks day while drinking one out of a Guinness glass. Cascades beautifully enough to inspire tears in the eyes of poets. dark brown/black, with a thick velvety nitrous head. nose of chocolate, coffee, licorice. flavor is roasted malts, black coffee, chocolate. nice lacing. finish is slightly bitter, coffee, malty. smooth and silky.
